<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. NEIL SOLOMON: NURSING AND ALCOHOL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: There's been a lot of information in newspapers and magazines and on 
television about the harm that can be done to the baby if a pregnant woman 
drinks. 
</P>
<P>
But I don't remember reading anything about what might happen to the baby if a 
nursing mother drinks. Could this have a harmful effect on the baby? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: As is true in the case of pregnant women, the safest course of action 
for nursing mothers is not to drink at all. Obviously, alcohol that has not 
been consumed cannot affect the baby. However, there is some evidence to 
suggest that no more than one alcoholic drink a day is permissible for nursing 
mothers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA060190-0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 227082 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 1, 1990, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
