<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: SUSPECTS RELEASED IN HATE-CRIME BURGLARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two reputed members of a skinhead gang were released from jail Thursday while 
investigators attempted to gather more evidence that they broke into a Palmdale 
woman's new home and scrawled threats, swastikas and satanic symbols on the 
walls, Los Angeles County sheriff's deputies said. 
</P>
<P>
Michael Todd Evans, 18, of Palmdale, and Thomas Conroy, 19, a transient, were 
arrested Tuesday on suspicion of burglary and vandalism after deputies said 
their footprints resembled those found at the crime scene, Sgt. Ron Shreves 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The men were released because detectives did not have enough evidence, he said. 
</P>
<P>
The vandalism was discovered Tuesday by a contractor working in the development 
that Mary Termini, 66, was moving into. 
</P>
<P>
Sheriff's gang experts have determined the graffiti apparently came from a 
local skinhead gang, Shreves said. Investigators theorized that the house of 
Termini, who is white, was randomly selected by the vandals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
