<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SANTA ANA; 
</P>
<P>
SLAYER OF SUSPECT WON'T BE CHARGED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prosecutors have decided not to press charges against a 29-year-old Anaheim man 
who fatally shot a suspected car burglar while waiting for police to arrive. 
</P>
<P>
Harvey Dean Dunn told investigators that he tried to hold Tony M. Martinez, 20, 
of Santa Ana and another suspected burglar at gunpoint in his car until police 
arrived. 
</P>
<P>
But he fired a shot when Martinez got out of the car, threatened him and began 
walking toward him. 
</P>
<P>
Martinez was pronounced dead of a single gunshot wound to the head outside an 
apartment complex at 900 S. Park Circle, police said. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Dist. Atty. Patrick H. Donahue said Thursday that he concluded that Dunn 
acted in self-defense because of Martinez's threats. 
</P>
<P>
"They were definitely threatening words," Donahue said. "They were threatening 
to his life." 
</P>
<P>
Murder charges will not be filed against the second burglary suspect, Martin 
Rodriguez Valdez, 23, of Santa Ana, but he has been charged with felony auto 
burglary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
