</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
George Steinbrenner's patience appears to be wearing thin as the New York 
Yankees continue to stumble, and Manager Bucky Dent could be one of the 
casualties. 
</P>
<P>
"Nobody is more disappointed than I am," the team's owner told the New York 
Times after the Yankees returned from a 2-6 road trip. 
</P>
<P>
"I've been very patient with Bucky. I haven't said a harsh word; in fact, I've 
been very encouraging. But I can see what everybody else sees." 
</P>
<P>
The Times reported today that sources say Steinbrenner already is mulling major 
changes within the Yankees organization after a 17-27 start, their worst since 
1925. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, outfielder Mel Hall ripped his teammates for their lack of desire. 
</P>
<P>
"The intensity here stinks," Hall told the New York Daily News. "It's almost as 
if we don't have guts. We just have to have more heart. I don't see it here." 
</P>
